<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-170-584  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 170 584.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 10 1989 v23 n15 p27(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Northrop's mountain of paper now a molehill.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Daly, James.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Northrop Corp automates the documentation of its assembly workwith its Integrated Management Planning and Control for Assemblysystem.andP;  The documentation relates to assembly work on the F-A-18Hornet fighter jet.andP;  Over 16,000 pages of documentation on thework have been converted into a package of 36 four-by-six-inchmicrofiche cards.andP;  In the past, Northrop clerks delivered bluebinders to assemblers detailing their shift's work.andP;  The fileswere updated daily, but could not automatically account forproblem situations, such as sick days or broken parts.andO;Documentation is now computerized and available instantly givingworkers the same information simultaneously.andP;  Northrop officialssay changing work orders is accomplished in 30 seconds, update anddistribution of work plans is performed automatically and thesystem will save $21 million over the remaining life of theproject.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Northrop Corp. (automation).andO;Ticker:    NOC.andO;Topic:     DocumentationAutomationInformation SystemsWork MeasurementAerospace Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>